John Edward: Language skills, essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record on academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students from Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide services at the highest level to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for high school and higher education, chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable topic of choice within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will reach his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest promotion rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools demonstrated that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish got such a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, languages, as matter, are held the same as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and other fields.
A survey conducted by the British Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that for the reasons employers gave for the struggle to fill vacancies, 17% were attributed to a language skills shortage.
Therefore, increasingly, language skills become imperative for preparing young people for their future career.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov on over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit, 15% percentage.
That is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
With more languages, especially in developing countries, children will be more likely to find significant jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn the languages that are considered to be most important to the United Kingdom when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, there will always be more languages of choice in independent schools, with teachers who specialize in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so that it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
