The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance as well as general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and chief executive of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within a section the image of a dorm room is presented, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, pants and books to be told what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
"We know that we cannot change the behavior of students instantly.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he also says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure imposed on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain believe that the body is hungry, which makes the students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course, after attending one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
