World Wide Web inventor plans to set up a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a Solid-based company, Berners-Lee's open-source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who is entitled to access the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is "global domination".
"Now we have to do it," he talked about the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data archives" or PODs.
It may contain contact lists, programs, calendars, music libraries or other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in one browser, all at once.
What is unique about this online personal data archive is that the user has complete control over who can access this type of information.
The company calls this "personal consolidation through data".
According to the company's CEO, John Bruce, the idea is for Inrupt to contribute adequate resources, processes and skills, so as to make Solid available to everyone.
Currently, the company is composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, a team of developers working on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee stated that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change when their business models are completely messed up at once.
"We're not asking their permission."
In a post published on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "The Inrupt mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of a new Internet on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when it created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Even after launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic for this next era of the Internet," Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: The cleric who won the Victoria Cross in World War I is celebrated
The only Church of England clergyman to win a Victoria Cross medal as a combatant in World War I was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann won the medal on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he had been awarded Britain's highest military honor.
A commemorative stone was unveiled Saturday by his two grandchildren during the parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of the grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "wonderfully symbolic" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years after the deed by which his grandfather won the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal of Saint-Quentin "through a very dense fog and under intense artillery and machine gun fire".
Later, he rushed to the front line and, with "a fantastic bravery", paved the way for the soldiers, then attacked an artillery nest alone and managed to eliminate three of the detachment's weapons.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "one thing I know I will never be able to equal, but that makes me feel humble".
He, along with his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a crown after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Orchestra.
Michael Vann said that he "feel very honored to play a role in the parade" and added that "the value of a genuine hero is demonstrated by the support a lot of people give him".
