Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to all because of his sexuality, but this motivated him to be successful.
The 24-year-old athlete said he didn't realize until he got to school that "not everyone is like me".
Invited to the first Desert Island Discs show presented by Lauren Laverne, on Radio 4, he said he was talking about gay people's rights to give others "hope".
The athlete also said that when he became a parent, he cared less about the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the usual presenter of the tradition show, will be missing for a few months due to an illness.
Invited in the first edition presented by Laverne, Daley said that when he was a child he felt "inferior" to others because "it was socially unacceptable to like both boys and girls."
He said: "To date, these feelings of inferiority and the fact that I felt different, were the real things that gave me strength and endurance to achieve success."
He wanted to prove he was "someone," he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they would eventually learn about his sexuality.
The winner of two bronze medals at the Olympics became a renowned supporter of LGBT campaigns and took advantage of appearing at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on several countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he decided to speak because he felt lucky to be able to live freely, without consequences, and because he wants to give others "hope".
The triple world champion said he "was taken by surprise" by falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black.
Daley married the Academy Award-winning filmmaker last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never an issue.
"When you go through so much at such a young age" - he participated in the first Olympics when he was only 14, and his father died of cancer after three years - he said, it's hard to find someone the same age who went through the same good and bad times.
The two became, in June, the parents of a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, which, Daley says, changed his "whole perspective".
"If I had been asked last year, I would have been interested in nothing but winning a gold medal," he said.
"You know what? There are more important things than gold medals at the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011, at the age of 40, after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father did not accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he wanted was to find out if they had received tickets for the 2012 London Olympics, because he wanted to be in the first place.
"I couldn't tell him «you won't be able to be in the first place, Father»," he said.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and it was only after he stopped breathing and died that I finally accepted that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
"I knew that this was what I had dreamed of my whole life, to jump in front of the spectators of my country at the Olympics, there is no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired him in the chosen music, Proud by Heather Small, a song that encouraged him before the Olympics and still thrills him.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15.
