Germany's new warship postponed again
Germany's newest naval force frigate should have been put into operation in 2014 to replace obsolete Cold War warships, but this will not happen until next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The entry into service of the ship "Rheinland-Pfalz", the banner ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigate class, was now delayed until the first half of 2019, according to the Die Zeit newspaper, which cites a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been introduced into the maritime forces in 2014, but problems after delivery affected this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships the Navy commanded in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
They are expected to be fitted with a strong cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-vas missiles, as well as stealth technologies, which provide a low radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for new frigates to be able to go on two-year missions without returning to the original port.
However, continued delays mean that these state-of-the-art warships, which are said to increase Germany's maritime force, will already be obsolete before entering service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate F125 was discussed in the press last year, when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Not much information is available about the reasons for the refusal, but the German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that would have made the warship useless on a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important because Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels would be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the crews on the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it was proven that the vessel was many too heavy, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future endowments.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is believed to be twice as heavy as vessels used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty mechanisms, and the price of the entire project, including that of crew training, has become a cause for concern.
