It deplored the fact that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates came into operation within the Navy.
National Trust Spys on the Secret Life of Bats
New research that is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use their environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the discoveries will reveal new things about the behavior of these novel flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will analyze common dwarf bats and pygmies bats, as well as ear bats and water bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be located in key places around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and which species emit certain sounds.
A map of the habitat and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scale-based picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a consultant on nature conservation for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as lawn creation, and which is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout Britain have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by construction and development work affecting their nests, but also habitat loss.
Wind turbines and public lighting are also risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, bats aren't blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, thinks very seriously of bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically conduct studies, control nests and sometimes conduct rescue missions.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threate estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of ten species of bats are found in Scotland.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here, at Threave, the area is wonderful for bats," he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand what they need to multiply."
It emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance work at properties, as mere unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and cubs, which can destroy all the local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are forbidden actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official within the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
This said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don't know how populations evolve for many of our species."
