How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The rescues that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening and, although there seems to be a long way to go before it ends, quarrels between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued his first warning earlier this year, by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar, steel and aluminium panels.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (£150 billion), effectively applying taxes to half of all goods in China reaching the territory of the United States.
Beijing has retaliated each time, most recently imposing a fee of between 5 and 10% for US products worth $60 billion.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly ceding to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, United States pressures on trade war could positively support China in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would in fact be more dangerous than what has been expected so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focusing on Asia at the Center for New American Security (Center for New American Security), a group of experts.
Syria ready for refugee return, Foreign Affairs Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war that has lasted more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Affairs Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, on-site conditions are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to get things back to normal.
Existing conditions allow refugees to voluntarily return to the country they have had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at everyday life and their livelihood.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
