Red tide news: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Florida's newest wildlife protection commission report shows a general drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of Tampa Gulf.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting lower concentrations.
This inflorescence of the red tide extends over a coast area of about 210 km, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County or off-site, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in Lee County and off-site and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory tract irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in the northwestern U.S. state of Florida in the past week.
